==== MCD Patches ====

<div style="background:#ffdddd;">
'''DISCLAIMER'''

MCD Patches are '''NOT''' meant for mods and modders!
* they don't offer any advantages over direct MCD manipulation; but suffer several disadvantages

'''Recommendation from OXC and OXCE devs:''' Modders should modify MCD files directly.
</div>

Redefines specific values of MCD files (including tile armor, HEBlock, TUWalk, etc.). The numbers after the #-symbol are representive to the offsets of the [[MCD|MCD files]]

{| class="wikitable" width="100%"
! width="150"| Value
! width="*"  | Description
! width="80" | Default
|-
| '''type'''
| Filename of the MCD file.
| ''required''
|-
| '''bigWall'''
| Type of BigWall, byte #33. 1 = solid block, 2 = diagonal (--), 3 = diagonal (l), 4 = west wall, 5 = north wall, 6 = east wall, 7 = south wall, 8 = south and east wall, 9 = north and west wall
| -
|-
| '''TUWalk'''
| TU cost to walk on this tile, byte #39. Walking is ground movement by any unit with movementType 0 or 1. If tile is an object or wall, TU cost is added to the TU cost of the floor tile under it.
| -
|-
| '''TUFly'''
| TU cost to fly on this tile, byte #41. Flying is movement not tied to the ground. Some flying units (movementType 1) still walk whenever there is a floor tile underneath them. If tile is an object or wall, TU cost is added to the TU cost of the floor tile under it.
| -
|-
| '''TUSlide'''
| TU cost to slide on this tile, byte #40. Siding is ground movement by any unit with movementType 2. (Example: Snakeman.) If tile is an object or wall, TU cost is added to the TU cost of the floor tile under it.
| -
|-
| '''deathTile'''
| The tile to replace once this tile is destroyed, byte #44. DeathTile must be within the same MCD and cannot use 0 or 1. If You set DeathTile to 0 or 1, they become either air (nothing) (0) or scorched earth (1) from BLANKS.MCD. While a map file cannot initially contain anything beyond its 256 max tile list (0-253 plus BLANKS), OpenXcom is able to render tiles outside of this range during battlescape gameplay. So the final MCD tileset in the terrain's list of tiles may contain some tiles within the 256 limit which are placed initially, and which can then die to become tiles which are outside the limit.
| -
|-
| '''terrainHeight'''
| Height of terrain, byte #48. Used for object tiles. One tile "cube" is 24 voxels in height, and you use negative values to raise the "floor height" of the tile. So a value of -12 would be halfway to the top. Positive values can be used to make its floor sink below the tile.
| -
|-
| '''specialType'''
| Type of tile, used primarily in after-mission item recovery, byte #59. 0 = nothing special; 1 = X-Com entry (used to spawn X-Com units); 2 = UFO Power Source (which has a 75% chance of exploding when the battlescape loads if it is a crash site); 3 = UFO Navigation; 4 = UFO Construction; 5 = Alien Food (UFO), Alien Cryogenics (TFTD); 6 = Alien Reproduction (UFO), Alien Cloning (TFTD); 7 = Alien Entertainment (UFO), Alien Learning Arrays (TFTD); 8 = Alien Surgery (UFO), Genetic Implanter (TFTD); 9 = Examination Room; 10 = Alien Alloys (UFO), Aqua Plastics (TFTD) - by default 10 of these tiles recovers for one unit from a UFO/USO, while 150 tiles recover for one unit from alien base/colony - see recoveryDividers to change this; 11 = Alien Habitat (UFO), Re-animation Zone (TFTD); 12 = damaged UFO tile; 13 = exit point (used to move to next map for the same mission); 14 = alien brain (UFO), T'Leth supports (TFTD) (boss tiles: destroy any of these to win the game). You can define higher numbers for recovery in OpenXcom as long as you put a corresponding specialType of the same value on the ruleset items entry which shall be recovered. But beware, MCDs with specialType greater than 14 may crash your map editor.
| -
|-
| '''explosive'''
| Explosion Strength, byte #55. Changing this value also seems to change the tile's HE_Type:54 value to 0 (high explosive). Most vanilla explosive tiles are type 1 (smoke). There is currently no way to edit the explosive type via mcdPatches.
| -
|-
| '''flammability'''
| Threshold to turn this tile on fire, byte #45. Similar to the tile's armor value, if this value is exceeded with an explosive blast (high explosive type), it will ignite.
| -
|-
| '''fuel'''
| The amount of turns this tile will burn for, byte #57. Seems to be based on fire from tile igniting due to flammability value, and doesn't affect fire caused by an incendiary blast.
| -
|-
| '''footstepSound'''
| Index of the footstep sound, byte #52. 1 = metal, 2 = normal, 3 = furniture? or mountain grass, 4 = water, 5 = sand, 6 = Martian sand (original DOS version), snow (Collector's Edition and most modern editions), 7 = snow (DOS version)
| -
|-
| '''HEBlock'''
| [[Explosions#HE Block|HE Blockage]] Byte #43.
| -
|-
| '''noFloor'''
| Byte #32. 1 = non-flying units will fall through; 0 = units can stand on it.
| -
|-
| '''LOFTS'''
| [[LOFTEMPS.DAT|LOFTEMPS.DAT]] Line Of Fire Template (LOFT) for the tile described as a vector, bytes #8 - #19. Each value corresponds to an index on the LOFT spritesheet and determines the voxel shape of the tile's hitbox. 
| -
|-
| '''stopLOS'''
| Byte #31. 1 = tile blocks vision like a bigwall 1; 0 = tile only blocks vision based on its LOFTs. In some cases setting this to 1 may improve performance.
| -
|-
| '''objectType'''
| Tile type, byte #53. 0 = floor; 1 = west wall; 2 = north wall; 3 = object. Determines how the tile functions when it appears dynamically as a death tile. Does not control how tiles are placed in the map files, however your map editor can reference this and color-code tiles to advise you on its intended placement. May affect tunnels.
| -
|}

